              "heading_path": [
                "Managing Dollar and Currency Exposure for Brazilian Investors",
                "When to Hedge vs. Accept FX Risk"
              ],
              "passage_text": "There is no universal answer, but a structured decision framework helps:\n\n**Hedge when**:\n- You have specific future USD obligations with a defined timeline\n- The hedge cost is modest relative to the potential downside\n- Your portfolio is already concentrated in global risk assets that would suffer in a risk-off environment (dollar appreciation would partially offset equity losses)\n- BRL is near what you believe to be fair value or slightly overvalued\n\n**Accept FX risk when**:\n- The cost of hedging is prohibitively high (e.g., cupom cambial is narrow, implying expensive hedge costs)\n- You have a long enough time horizon to absorb volatility\n- Your dollar-denominated assets themselves provide diversification value through underlying economic exposure (US equities, real assets)\n- BRL appears deeply undervalued relative to purchasing power parity or commodity-justified levels\n\n**Dynamic hedging**: Some institutional investors use rules-based dynamic hedging — increasing hedge ratios as BRL appreciates toward fair value, reducing them as BRL falls. This approach aims to buy insurance when it is cheap and reduce it when it becomes expensive.\n\n---",
              "start": 0,
