          "kind": "answer",
          "answer": "Brazilian exporters with USD revenues and BRL costs are structurally long USD: BRL appreciation hurts them, while BRL depreciation tends to help sectors with dollarized revenues and local-cost bases such as mining, export agribusiness, pulp, and aircraft manufacturers.[1][3]\n\nThe standard hedge is to sell USD exposure forward: sell DOL/WDO dollar futures on B3, sell USD via offshore NDFs where appropriate, use ACC/export pre-payment to convert future receivables into BRL upfront, or use a swap cambial structured as receive BRL CDI and pay USD plus FX variation, which Decade describes as economically equivalent to selling USD forward.[1]\n\nIn agribusiness, Decade describes a typical program as partial rather than full: soy farmers often hedge 30–50% of expected harvest through dollar futures or ACC during the planting/growing season, with the hedge ratio driven by the BRL/USD breakeven needed to make the crop viable given local costs.[1]\n\nFor commodity producers, FX hedging is only one leg of the risk program: a Brazilian soybean farmer faces both the USD commodity price risk and the BRL/USD FX risk, so the combined hedge may require selling CBOT or B3 commodity futures for the commodity leg and selling DOL/WDO on B3 for the FX leg, thereby locking the BRL-equivalent revenue.[1]\n\nA practical implementation point is that futures-based dollar hedges embed the local-versus-foreign interest-rate differential: Decade notes that dollar futures exposure reflects covered-interest-parity economics and that, when Brazilian rates are high versus U.S. rates, the cupom cambial can be a meaningful carry component.[2]",
