              "passage_text": "A robust Brazilian dividend portfolio is built on five principles:\n\n**1. Sector diversification**: No more than 40% of dividend income derived from a single sector. The ideal allocation spans utilities (30–40%), financials (20–30%), telecoms (15–20%), and a smaller satellite allocation to natural resources and other dividend-paying sectors.\n\n**2. Quality over yield**: Prefer a 7% yield from a brAAA-equivalent credit quality regulated utility over a 14% yield from a company with balance sheet stress or governance concerns. The total return of the former consistently outperforms.\n\n**3. Distribution calendar awareness**: Map out the expected distribution timeline across holdings. Most Brazilian companies pay once or twice per year; constructing a portfolio with staggered distribution dates can create a smoother income stream.\n\n**4. JCP maximization**: Where two companies offer similar business quality, prefer the one that makes extensive use of JCP (providing corporate-level tax efficiency) over one that distributes solely through taxable dividends.\n\n**5. Regular fundamental review**: Dividend sustainability is not static. Regulatory changes (tariff reviews for utilities), competitive dynamics (new technology disruption in telecoms), and balance sheet evolution must be monitored continuously. A semi-annual fundamental review of dividend sustainability metrics — payout ratio, FCF coverage, leverage — is the minimum standard.\n\n**Target portfolio construction** (illustrative):\n\n| Allocation | Sector | Representative Names |\n|------------|--------|----------------------|\n| 30–35% | Electric Utilities | ISA CTEEP, Engie Brasil, Alupar, CPFL |\n| 20–25% | Banking / Financials | Itaú, Banco do Brasil |\n| 15–20% | Telecommunications | Vivo/Telefônica, TIM |\n| 10–15% | Oil & Gas | Petrobras (with sizing discipline) |\n| 5–10% | Infrastructure / Other | Sanepar, Sabesp (post-privatization), others |\n\n---",
              "start": 0,
              "end": 1917
