              "heading_path": [
                "Dividend Aristocrats of Brazil: Building a Sustainable Income Portfolio on B3",
                "What Makes a Dividend Aristocrat in the Brazilian Context?"
              ],
              "passage_text": "In the US context, dividend aristocracy is defined by longevity — 25 consecutive years of dividend increases, embedded in the S&P 500 Dividend Aristocrats methodology. This threshold is unreachable for most Brazilian companies, given the country's economic volatility history: the hyperinflation of the 1980s and early 1990s, the 1999 BRL devaluation, the 2002 pre-election crisis, the 2015–2016 severe recession, and the 2020 pandemic shock all created genuine discontinuities in corporate earnings and dividend policies.\n\nA more appropriate Brazilian definition of a dividend aristocrat encompasses:\n\n**Track record**: Consistent dividend payments (in BRL terms) for at least 7–10 consecutive years without omission.\n\n**Yield meaningfulness**: A dividend yield (DY) that meaningfully exceeds the inflation rate — providing real income, not merely nominal distributions.\n\n**Payout sustainability**: Dividends supported by genuine free cash flow, not accounting-driven distributions that deplete the balance sheet.\n\n**Predictability**: A business model (regulated monopoly, concession, financial franchise) where future earnings streams are reasonably foreseeable, enabling dividend planning for both the company and the investor.\n\n**Governance commitment**: Management teams and controlling shareholders with a stated commitment to shareholder distributions, ideally embedded in corporate bylaws or official dividend policies.\n\nThis framework identifies a manageable universe of Brazilian names — primarily in utilities, financial services, telecommunications, and natural resources — where income investing can be pursued with institutional rigor.\n\n---",
