              "passage_text": "Currency gains for Brazilian individual investors carry specific tax treatment:\n\n**FX gains on foreign currency cash**: Gains from the appreciation of foreign currency held in bank accounts abroad are taxed at progressive IRPF rates (up to 27.5% for amounts above R$55,976/year). An important exemption exists: FX gains on foreign currency arising from the sale of goods (e.g., selling a property abroad) may benefit from a cost basis adjustment.\n\n**BDRs and international ETFs**: Capital gains from BDRs and ETFs are subject to the standard 15% capital gains rate for equity-type instruments. The BRL 20,000/month exemption for small gains, which applies to direct equity sales, does not apply to BDRs.\n\n**Dollar futures (DOL/WDO)**: Gains from financial derivatives (including dollar futures at B3) are taxed at 15% (Day trade: 20%). Losses can be offset against gains from other futures instruments.\n\n**Foreign investment funds**: The tax reform legislation introduced auto-taxation of offshore investment fund gains (the \"come-cotas\" equivalent for offshore), significantly changing the planning dynamics for Brazilian investors using international structures.\n\nCareful tax planning — ideally with a qualified Brazilian tax advisor familiar with international matters — is essential for investors holding meaningful FX exposure through multiple instrument types.\n\n---",
